post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_5295134_5295168_0": {"length": 21, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3367}}, "n3337": {"so_5295134_5295168_0": {"length": 21, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3237}}, "n4659": {"so_5295134_5295168_0": {"length": 13, "quality": 0.6190476190476191, "section_id": 4132}}}, "5295168": {"Id": "5295168", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Yes, it must be at least as restrictive (\u00a715.4/3):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_5295134_5295168_0\">If a virtual function has an exception-specification, all declarations, including the definition, of any function\n  that overrides that virtual function in any derived class shall only allow exceptions that are allowed by the\n  exception-specification of the base class virtual function.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "179910", "LastActivityDate": "2011-03-14T06:33:59.337", "Score": "16", "CreationDate": "2011-03-14T05:43:48.380", "ParentId": "5295134", "CommentCount": "2", "OwnerUserId": "179910", "LastEditDate": "2011-03-14T06:33:59.337"}, "5295134": {"ViewCount": "4537", "Body": "<p>If a class inherits from another and overrides a virtual function, how must the exception-specification for the derived (overridden) function be related to the base function?</p>\n<p>Is that is must be at least as restrictive? right? or others?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "5295168", "Title": "Exception specification when overriding a virtual function?", "CreationDate": "2011-03-14T05:36:28.897", "Id": "5295134", "CommentCount": "7", "FavoriteCount": "6", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditDate": "2011-08-23T23:02:50.407", "LastEditorUserId": "597607", "LastActivityDate": "2013-04-23T00:03:12.113", "Score": "13", "OwnerUserId": "435645", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "16158742": {"Id": "16158742", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It is $15.4 p.5 in <a href=\"http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2011/n3242.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2011/n3242.pdf</a>:\n\"If a virtual function has an exception-specification, all declarations, including the definition, of any function that overrides that virtual function in any derived class shall only allow exceptions that are allowed by the\nexception-specification of the base class virtual function\"</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-04-23T00:03:12.113", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2013-04-23T00:03:12.113", "ParentId": "5295134", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "2309292"}});